{{Use Australian English|date=January 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Infobox Ethnic group |group= Congolese Australians |pop=5,522 (by birth, 2016)<ref>Australian Bureau of Statistics 2016, Reflecting Australia - Stories from the Census 2016 - Cultural Diversity 'Table 1: Country of Birth of Person by State and Territory of Usual Residence' data cube: Excel spreadsheet, cat no. 2071.0, viewed 6 April 2018, http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/2071.02016?OpenDocument</ref> | popplace = Congolese-born people by state or territory | region1 = [[Queensland]] | pop1 = 1,562 | ref1 = | region2 = [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] | pop2 = 982 | ref2 = | region3 = [[Western Australia]] | pop3 = 952 | ref3 = | region4 = [[South Australia]] | pop4 = 901 | ref4 = |languages = [[French language|French]]{{·}}[[English language|English]]{{·}}[[Swahili language|Swahili]]<ref>https://www.dss.gov.au/our-responsibilities/settlement-and-multicultural-affairs/programs-policy/a-multicultural-australia/programs-and-publications/community-information-summaries/the-democratic-republic-of-congo-born-community</ref> |rels= [[Christianity]] |related= [[African Australians]] }} '''Congolese Australians''' are [[Australians]] of [[Congo Basin|Congolese]] descent or who were born in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] or the [[Republic of the Congo]]. The population of Congolese born Australians has increased significantly over the past 20 years, from just 21 at the [[Census in Australia#1996|1996 Census]] to 5,522 at the [[Census in Australia#2016|2016 Census]].<ref>Australian Bureau of Statistics 2014, Australian Historical Population Statistics 2014'*: Country of Birth' data cube: Excel spreadsheet, cat no. 3105.0.65.001, viewed 9 April 2018, http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/3105.0.65.0012014?OpenDocument</ref>
==History== Almost 75% of Congolese Australians have immmigrated from the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], which has experienced significant conflict and instability since gaining independence in 1960. This has resulted in around 1.8 million Congolese being internally displaced, with around 300,000 fleeing to neighbouring countries. Most immigrants from the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] have arrived in Australia after 2004 under the Australian Government's Humanitarian Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dss.gov.au/our-responsibilities/settlement-and-multicultural-affairs/programs-policy/a-multicultural-australia/programs-and-publications/community-information-summaries/the-democratic-republic-of-congo-born-community|title=The Democratic Republic of Congo-born Community {{!}} Department of Social Services, Australian Government|website=www.dss.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-09}}</ref> Over 650 visas were issued to people from the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] under the Australian Government Humanitarian programme in 2015-16, being the fifth highest country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homeaffairs.gov.au/about/corporate/information/fact-sheets/60refugee|title=Fact sheet - Australia's Refugee and Humanitarian programme {{!}} Department of Home Affairs, Australian Government|website=www.homeaffairs.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-04-09}}</ref> Between 2010-2016 Congolese refugees were in the top 10 nationalities accepted into Australia every year.<ref>[https://www.sbs.com.au/topics/life/article/2016/08/22/here-are-exact-countries-australia-taking-refugees DRC Refugees to Australia] SBS. 03/10/16</ref>
