[[File:Dying gaul.jpg|right|thumb|''[[Dying Gaul]]'', anonymous Roman sculpture]]

The practice of entering [[combat]] without the use of clothing and armor is rare; apart from the social aspects of [[nudity]], the combatant lacks even the basic protection of clothes, for instance when diving for cover or crawling. Also the combatant misses the practicality of hiding/carrying objects in pockets and attached to clothes.

The artistic convention of [[heroic nudity]], however, was established in the [[Art in ancient Greece|art of ancient Greece]] by the Archaic period.

== History ==

=== Celtic peoples ===

[[The Histories (Polybius)|Polybius' Histories]] describe how the [[Gaesatae]], hired by other Celtic peoples, the [[Boii]] and [[Insubres]] as mercenaries to fight the Romans, stood naked at the head of their army at the [[Battle of Telamon]] in 225BC.<ref name="pers_Poly">{{Cite web | title = Histories, book 2, The Gauls Defeated On Their Way Home | author = Polybius|author-link=Polybius | work = perseus.tufts.edu | date = 110 BCE | accessdate = 2016-06-03 | url = http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Plb.+2.28&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0234 | language =   | at= Book 2 Ch 28 }}</ref> [[Diodorus Siculus]] reported other instances of such combat: "Some use iron breast-plates in battle, while others fight naked, trusting only in the protection which nature gives."{{sfn|Stephen Allen|2001|p=3}} Another possible reason for this was to avoid infection of wounds caused by contact with contaminated clothing and debris.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

[[Livy]] tells of how the [[Tolistobogii]] of [[Galatia]] fought naked, being proud of their spilt blood and even widening gashes they received themselves. <ref> [[Livy]], [[Ab Urbe Condita]], Book XXXVIII, Chapter 21</ref>

[[Julius Caesar]] records in [[de Bello Gallico|his account of the Gallic War]] that the [[Gaul]]s went into battle naked save for their weapons.

Sometimes the soldiers wore no clothing but were covered in war paint, a custom that allegedly gave the [[Picts]] their name.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

== Modern occurrences ==

In some present [[martial arts]] which are designed to be fit for military fighting, full or partial nudity still occurs. The traditional ''donga'' style of [[stick fighting]] practiced by the young warriors, now bearing firearms, of the [[Omo River (Ethiopia)|Omo Valley]] [[Surma people|Suri tribe]] of South Sudan and western Ethiopia, is often practiced entirely naked: serious injury is not uncommon, and it is occasionally fatal.{{cn|date=June 2016}} Another example is the stick fighting style of the neighbouring [[Nyangatom people|Nyangatom]], which fight [[bare-chested]]; the goal is to mark the adversary with visible stripes on the back.{{cn|date=June 2016}}

In the [[Vietnam War]], [[Vietcong]] [[sapper]]s used to slip through the barbed wire naked or almost naked.{{sfn|Don Winslow|2004|p=367}}

In modern [[Liberia]], soldiers under [[Joshua Blahyi|"General Butt Naked" Joshua Blahyi]] fought naked in order to terrorize their opponents.{{sfn|Tony Tate|2004|p=26}}

